      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A local healthcare facility is looking to update its waste management system. They are considering adopting the screw feed technology for disposal of infectious waste. What is the primary result of utilizing screw feed technology in this context?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5382220",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 34717,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        7
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. B. 80% reduction in volume and 35% reduction in weight.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Explanation -&nbsp;</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>SCREW FEED TECHNOLOGY</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Non-burn dry thermal disinfection&nbsp;</strong>process in which <strong>waste</strong> is <strong>shredded</strong> and then <strong>heated</strong> in a <strong>rotating auger</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">The <strong>waste</strong> is <strong>reduced</strong> by <strong>80 percent</strong> in <strong>volume</strong> and by <strong>20—35 percent</strong> in <strong>weight</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">This process is suitable for <strong>treating infectious waste</strong> and <strong>sharps</strong>, but it should <strong>not</strong> be used to Process <strong>pathological</strong>, <strong>cytotoxic</strong>, or <strong>radio-active waste.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Educational Objective:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Screw feed technology</strong>, a <strong>non-burn method</strong>, <strong>reducing</strong> <strong>volume</strong> by <strong>80%</strong> and <strong>weight</strong> by <strong>20-35%,</strong> is suitable for <strong>infectious &amp; sharp waste</strong> but <strong>not</strong> for <strong>pathological, cytotoxic</strong> or <strong>radioactive waste.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Reference: Park 26<sup>th</sup> ed pg. 885</strong></span></p>",
      "correct_choice_id": 24982,
